**Installing Arduino**  
To get started, make sure the **Arduino application** is installed on your computer or laptop. If it hasn't been installed yet, visit the [Arduino website](https://www.arduino.cc/en/software/) to download and install it.

![Arduino IDE Download Page](image-50.png)

![Arduino Download Options](../images/Installing_Arduino_236_Getting_Started1.JPG) 

On the Arduino download page, choose the version that matches your computer’s operating system.

**For Windows users**:

![Windows Download Options](../images/Installing_Arduino_236_Getting_Started2.JPG) 

* **Do not** select the **.zip file** option.  
* Instead, choose either **"Windows 64-bit App"** or **"Windows Installer"** for proper installation.

  **After the download is complete:**

  * **On a Mac**: The zip file may appear on your **Desktop** or in your **Downloads** folder.  
  * **On Windows**: The zip file will typically be found in your **Downloads** folder or on your **Desktop**.

![Mac Installation](../images/Installing_Arduino_236_Getting_Started3.JPG) 

**On a Mac**:

* Open the downloaded zip file.  
* The Arduino application will appear—**drag it into your  Applications folder** to install it.


**On Windows**:

* Open the file you downloaded—either the **64-bit App** or the **MSI Installer**.  
* Follow the prompts to complete the installation.

---

**Arduino Environment**

![Arduino IDE Interface](../images/Installing_Arduino_236_Getting_Started4.JPG) 

Now that the Arduino application has been installed successfully, open it. The Arduino IDE should look ← something like this.

←  This is where the code is written to run Arduino programs.

←  Any error messages will appear **in the margins of the black console window** when you run your code.

**Installing Adafruit Packages and Libraries**

Before running any programs on your **Arduino,** you must install a few essential packages and libraries.

Without these, the Arduino won’t be able to execute your code.

**Install Adafruit Libraries**

**This initial installation is required to give the Arduino application access to specific Adafruit libraries you'll need.**

**Step 1**. To install this package, click on the Arduino drop-down menu and select Preferences:  						  

![alt text](../images/Installing_Arduino_236_Getting_Started5.JPG)
			

![alt text](image-51.png)

Once the link has been copied, go to the Arduino application on your laptop/pc and click on Arduino \-\>Settings

To install this package, you need to copy this link:   **↓**

### **https://adafruit.github.io/arduino-board-index/package\_adafruit\_index.json**

Paste the link you copied in “Additional Boards Manager URLs”

![alt text](../images/Installing_Arduino_236_Getting_Started7.JPG)

Click “Ok” and close the Arduino Application

![alt text](../images/Installing_Arduino_236_Getting_Started8.JPG) Next, you will need to go to Tools \-\> Board \-\> Boards Manager

![alt text](../images/Installing_Arduino_236_Getting_Started9.JPG)

Now that you are done downloading the necessary boards on Boards Manager, close the Boards Manager window.

![alt text](../images/Installing_Arduino_236_Getting_Started10.JPG)

In the search bar type “Wifi 101” and install the library called “Wifi 101”

![alt text](../images/Installing_Arduino_236_Getting_Started16.JPG)

Repeat this step with the following libraries (For libraries that require other libraries to be installed, click install all when prompted):

* Adafruit Sleepy Dog   
* SparkFun SCD4X Arduino Library  
* Adafruit GFX  
* Adafruit SSD1306  
* Adafruit BME280  
* Adafruit SH110X  
* Sensirion I2C SEN5X  
* flashstorage  
* WIFI 101  
* Honeywell TruStability SPI

* RTClib.h  
  * Download from [Github](https://github.com/adafruit/RTClib)  
  * In Arduino IDE Select Sketch, then Include Library and click on add Zip Library then open the ZIP folder that you have just downloaded.

    

**Now you are done\!**   
Below are some additional instructions.

**Connecting Your Arduino \- Compiling and Uploading**

* Plug in your Arduino to your laptop using a Micro-USB Cable to your computer. (If you do not have a USB port on your computer you will need a adapter)  
    
![alt text](../images/Installing_Arduino_236_Getting_Started11.JPG)
    
    
    
    
    
    
    
    
    
    
* Launch Arduino IDE and select the correct port with the dropdown menu  
    
![alt text](../images/Installing_Arduino_236_Getting_Started12.JPG)
    
    
* When you have the correct port selected and you are ready to Compile code to your Arduino. First compile the code to check for any errors beforehand.

![alt text](../images/Installing_Arduino_236_Getting_Started13.JPG)

* When there are no errors present in under output. You can now upload the code to your Arduino

![alt text](../images/Installing_Arduino_236_Getting_Started14.JPG)


---

**Running Blink example: testing connections (Computer with Arduino)**

Now that you have all the libraries downloaded, you can test the connection between the Sensor and your computer. 

* Head to File \> Examples \> Basics \> Blink to pull up the blink code that can be used to test if the sensor is connected to your computer (Will need a adaptor to connect)  and can have code uploaded to it  
  * Upload the code and look at the sensor when the code finish uploading to check it the light is blinking

  **![alt text](../images/Installing_Arduino_236_Getting_Started15.JPG)**
